
[1]nutmeg

   NUT'MEG, n. [L. But it may be questionable whether the last syllable in
   English, meg, is not from L., mace, the bark that envelops the nut.]
   The fruit of a tree of the genus Myristica, growing in the isles of the
   East Indies and South Sea. The tree gorws to the gighth of thirty feet,
   producing numerous branches. The color of the bark of the trunk is a
   reddish brown; that of the young branches a bright green. The fruit is
   of the kind called drupe, that is, a pulpy pericarp without valves,
   containing a nut or kernel. The covering of this nut is the mace. The
   nutmeg is an aromatic, very grateful to the taste and smell, and much
   used in cookery.
